<subSubSection id="3DFA9FFE268A8ABB6678A66D1D669638" pageId="4" pageNumber="5" type="latin">
<paragraph id="6F1E7A24EA1DD84ADFA812B75F3CBFE7" pageId="4" pageNumber="5">Latin</paragraph>
<paragraph id="40B32E6F5E297B4EFDAFFCD8344D1D18" pageId="4" pageNumber="5">
Dilkea nitens 
<emphasis id="FFE711E5B8BE98F8F884A47508147DEB" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="5">foliis anguste ovatis a generis</emphasis>
Dilkea 
<emphasis id="BE9F8A050560D1B7BACBF62F18EC59CF" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="5">speciebus mihi notis distincta. Liana vel frutex; in Loreto (Peruvia) crescit</emphasis>
.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="5572CDB8F4266F98945AB8FD7AEBE9A6" pageId="4" pageNumber="5" type="type">
<paragraph id="783E7B608C8BB348ABA7B2E3112D4BE8" pageId="4" pageNumber="5">Type:</paragraph>
<paragraph id="BB0D3D4E08872EE9C411BA5838A9C6EA" pageId="4" pageNumber="5">
PERU. 
<emphasis id="2F02EC36BBD51571555D40A14A9F77BD" bold="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="5">Loreto:</emphasis>
Maynas, Pena Negra, 25 km SW of Iquitos, 3°38.6666'S, 73°20.15'W, 1 Aug 1972, fr., 
<emphasis id="D09C017BE879BD58F03185CCFF8CB3FA" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="5">T.B. Croat 18649</emphasis>
(holotype: US-2788507!; isotype: MO!)
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="63E81A2DF70C1AFB177CB06EAC0EE491" pageId="4" pageNumber="5">
&quot;Shrub or vine&quot; (fide 
<emphasis id="4A027DB5DAC19E0FDA4AE960E26B4B20" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="5">Croat 18649</emphasis>
), growth continuous, internodes subequal or varying gradually in size, twigs with internodes 0.5-1.5 cm long, drying pale brown; glabrous throughout. Stipules not seen. Leaf: petiole terete, 1.5-3 cm long, drying pale brown except for the basal 1/3-1/2 pulvinus, slightly swollen and drying black; blades coriaceous, narrowly ovate, 8.5-19 
<normalizedToken id="4FE3CD174C0B81E30F7022FF84F77B83" originalValue="×">x</normalizedToken>
5-6 cm, widest near base, base round, apex acute or round and 
<normalizedToken id="CD67B44257D5A4B445FEB29C41036B5A" originalValue="short–acuminate">short-acuminate</normalizedToken>
, margin undulated (in herb., probably because of the dorsiventrally curved midrib), drying pale brown, somewhat shiny, midrib dorsiventrally curved, adaxially raised, abaxially strongly raised, main veins clearly visible abaxially, 12-18 each side of the midrib of well-developed leaves. Inflorescences subterminal by abscission of the apical stem meristem; peduncle as thick as or thicker than the stem bearing it, much shorter than the petioles, ca. 5 mm long, forming apically a nearly flat surface bearing 1-6 flowers; bracts 
<normalizedToken id="CA6A58B644DCC7957ECB277668274176" originalValue="scale–like">scale-like</normalizedToken>
, triangular, less than 1 mm long; pedicels sub-null to 0.2 cm long. Flowers not seen. Fruits sub-spherical, 4 
<normalizedToken id="E34E0FEC403F7D7C5A6D2CF4F487ECB3" originalValue="×">x</normalizedToken>
3 cm including a 3-4 mm long narrow apical cone, wall less than 1 mm thick, rigid and brittle, seen immature green; seeds not seen, brown (fide 
<emphasis id="A149A773E6B631475CB10E77B5E7CCEC" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="5">Croat 18649</emphasis>
), few.
</paragraph>
<caption id="54F87ADDDA2A27FD23B02A638389FCBC" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/9856" pageId="4" pageNumber="5" start="Figure 2" startId="F2">
<paragraph id="DCB2040FC1C7EDE00B67DF3F45053E56" pageId="4" pageNumber="5">
<emphasis id="F0F4B6257F7DCB14D5353E681D788A09" bold="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="5">Figure 2.</emphasis>
Holotype of 
<taxonomicName id="1B0C5D2038A267F19AF3F522BD395F56" authorityName="Feuillet" authorityYear="2011" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Passifloraceae" genus="Dilkea" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF,CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="" order="Malpighiales" pageId="4" pageNumber="5" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="nitens">Dilkea nitens</taxonomicName>
Feuillet: 
<emphasis id="1E3C3936A218BCF74AF998AF82291038" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="5">T.B. Croat 18649</emphasis>
(US).
</paragraph>
</caption>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="68CE9922C0B1823FFD75834D7E8F98BE" pageId="4" pageNumber="5" type="distribution">
<paragraph id="6DF0371A5BCCFD666FAADDD222DCD386" pageId="4" pageNumber="5">Distribution.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="D416EE74DDB32DDE7D468009ACEB2B7E" pageId="4" pageNumber="5">
<taxonomicName id="C214BCA504625BB095F0AAABA6E32D21" authorityName="Feuillet" authorityYear="2011" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Passifloraceae" genus="Dilkea" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF,CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="" order="Malpighiales" pageId="4" pageNumber="5" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="nitens">Dilkea nitens</taxonomicName>
is known only by the type collection from Loreto (Peru). The geographical coordinates are taken from a gazetteer (
<bibRefCitation id="8D8CE90D93C0C7A806C30AA9DA747361" author="USBGN," journalOrPublisher="Defense Mapping Agency, Washington" pageId="5" pageNumber="6" refId="B8" refString="USBGN, , 1989. Gazetteer of Peru, 2nd edition. Defense Mapping Agency, Washington, 869 pp." title="Gazetteer of Peru, 2 nd edition." year="1989">USBGN 1989</bibRefCitation>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="4FA4F3FAF19A9AFAA56CFDB1BFE88A65" pageId="4" pageNumber="5" type="ecology">
<paragraph id="49CAA5F8FEF64656B9D9497000F93C36" pageId="4" pageNumber="5">Ecology.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="478BB43A2BBD1575F3815A7CAC87AC69" pageId="4" pageNumber="5">The label does not give any information about the habitat.</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="6A86AF4F01B1FC1A77345FFDF819E7B5" pageId="4" pageNumber="5" type="phenology">
<paragraph id="0D6830F8A3C2E1815290D900AC39CC84" pageId="4" pageNumber="5">Phenology.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="AB077E43FEAAEF4BE1F8688C989E716F" pageId="4" pageNumber="5">It had immature fruits in August.</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="F68812C7A7E9A8D5F6300559AD2F6EB9" pageId="4" pageNumber="5" type="preliminary conservation status">
<paragraph id="919FCA28A80DD00BC67CDA4A94D5AFB2" pageId="4" pageNumber="5">Preliminary conservation status.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="0DE09CBEAD535CA9FC666C94EF27B11D" pageId="4" pageNumber="5">
<taxonomicName id="2626247C63970AF56603DC9A85E65177" authorityName="Feuillet" authorityYear="2011" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Passifloraceae" genus="Dilkea" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF,CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="" order="Malpighiales" pageId="4" pageNumber="5" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="nitens">Dilkea nitens</taxonomicName>
is only known from the type collection from Maynas, Loreto, Peru. The data are insufficient to assess an informed status for this species, therefore I suggest that it be classified as DD (Data Deficient) according to 
<bibRefCitation id="5D0A5F06EE9E46E51BE0567B1B4D9846" author="IUCN," journalOrPublisher="IUCN Species Survival Commission, IUCN, Gland, Switzerland and Cambridge, UK" pageId="5" pageNumber="6" refId="B6" refString="IUCN, , 2001. IUCN Red List Categories and Criteria: Version 3.1. IUCN Species Survival Commission, IUCN, Gland, Switzerland and Cambridge, UK" title="IUCN Red List Categories and Criteria: Version 3.1." year="2001">IUCN (2001</bibRefCitation>
, 
<bibRefCitation id="6D7461F6C3AE78C42775075CAE35194A" author="IUCN," journalOrPublisher="IUCN Species Survival Commision" pageId="5" pageNumber="6" refId="B7" refString="IUCN, , 2003. Guidelines for Application of IUCN Red List Criteria at Regional Levels: Version 3.0. IUCN Species Survival Commision" title="Guidelines for Application of IUCN Red List Criteria at Regional Levels: Version 3.0." year="2003">2003</bibRefCitation>
) categories.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="3A3CF6635F7EF843F7312C5B5110D8B2" pageId="4" pageNumber="5" type="discussion">
<paragraph id="29DC508B95792B002D1C103EF0B5D536" pageId="4" pageNumber="5">Discussion.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="1B4158BF7556938195080CD2A7FE9D32" pageId="4" pageNumber="5">
In subgenus 
<taxonomicName id="60A33A7903FFD5A44F5CE5017D4393AC" authorityName="Masters" authorityYear="1871" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Passifloraceae" genus="Dilkea" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF,CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="" order="Malpighiales" pageId="4" pageNumber="5" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="genus">Dilkea</taxonomicName>
where most species have oblanceolate to obovate leaf blades, 
<taxonomicName id="6D792EB144D4F5837D6C0C98A69DCA52" authorityName="Feuillet" authorityYear="2011" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Passifloraceae" genus="Dilkea" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF,CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="" order="Malpighiales" pageId="4" pageNumber="5" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="nitens">Dilkea nitens</taxonomicName>
is clearly identified by its narrowly ovate leaf blades, widest a quarter of the length from the base or less, a character shared only with 
<taxonomicName id="247DB655503C55CAFC6DB2C6B206956F" authorityName="A. C. Cervi" authorityYear="1991" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Passifloraceae" genus="Dilkea" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF,CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="" order="Malpighiales" pageId="4" pageNumber="5" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="margaritae">Dilkea margaritae</taxonomicName>
Cervi from Mato Grosso (Brazil) which, in contrast with 
<taxonomicName id="F2CABA09748B3A84FBF5A4482E473EC8" authorityName="Feuillet" authorityYear="2011" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Passifloraceae" genus="Dilkea" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF,CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="" order="Malpighiales" pageId="4" pageNumber="5" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="nitens">Dilkea nitens</taxonomicName>
, is a low shrub with 3.5-7 cm long axillary pedicels.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="2505440E9E3ED5587D155A53B1C07C7E" pageId="4" pageNumber="5" type="etymology">
<paragraph id="23A2C95D848A203E0705CB285C0090D7" pageId="4" pageNumber="5">Etymology.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="833836FF573E0BA51E63D1642F303800" pageId="4" pageNumber="5">
The epithet coming from the Latin adjective 
<emphasis id="D62DC8A9C271BC5EE618376B2BC486B3" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="5">nitens</emphasis>
(= shiny), refers to the upper surface of the leaves, in contrast with 
<taxonomicName id="15ED388DEAFAC5114C073EFADE55C8C0" authorityName="Feuillet" authorityYear="2011" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Passifloraceae" genus="Dilkea" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF,CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="" order="Malpighiales" pageId="4" pageNumber="5" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="hebes">Dilkea hebes</taxonomicName>
, another species from Loreto described above.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
